<div class="CWDInfo" id="CWDInfo">
  <div class="grid-item5">
        <div id="CWDInfohead">
            <h1>CWD - Chronic Waste Disease</h1>
        </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-item1">
      <div id="infop">
            <p>
                Chronic Waste Disease (CWD) is a prion disease that affects cervids, including the whitetail deer of Northern Illinois and Southern Wisconsin. CWD is fatal to deer, and there are no cures or vaccines. 
                <br>
                <br>
                CWD is a serious threat to the health and well being of wild and farmed deer populations. In addition to being devestating to deer herds, the long-term affect of CWD is unknown on humans.
                <br>
                <br>
                The ILDNR and CDC recommends hunters have venison samples checked for CWD at any check-in station, or the participating meat processors listed above. The CDC recommends you do not consume venison infected with CWD.
            </p>
        </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-item2">
        <img id="InfoImg1" alt="Deer with CWD" src="https://files.osgnetworks.tv/4/files/2018/09/whitetail-deer-lead.png"></img>
        <p id="InfoImg1P">A young whitetail showing late signs of CWD. Deer can be infected with CWD for years before it impacts their health.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-item3">
        <img id="InfoImg2" alt="Deer with CWD (2)" src="https://www.outdooralabama.com/sites/default/files/Hunting/CWD/19-CWD-Mike%20Hopper%2C%20Kansas%20Dept.%20of%20Wildlife%2C%20Parks%20and%20Tourism.JPG"></img>
        <p id="InfoImg2P">A mature buck with CWD. There is no vaccine or treatment for the disease at this time.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-item4">
        <div id=infol>
            <h6>To help reduce the spread of Chronic Waste Disease:</h6>
            <ul>
                <li>Test for CWD after your sucessful hunt!</li>
                <li>Eliminate the use of salt-licks and other attractants, that give deer surfaces to spread bodily fluid.</li>
                <li>Clean your boots after hiking in hunting areas.</li>
                <li>Always dispose of the brain and spinal cord, as this is where CWD is concentrated in deer.</li>
                <li>If your venison tests positive for CWD, dispose of it.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
  </div>

</div>


